1) What is JRE?
-->The Java Runtime Environment (JRE) is a software package that provides the necessary tools and libraries to run Java applications on a computer. 

2) What is included in JRE?
-->The Java Runtime Environment (JRE) comprises a Java Virtual Machine (JVM), Java class libraries (including rt.jar), and a Class Loader.
    It provides the minimum requirements—libraries, API, and Java Virtual Machine—necessary to run compiled Java applications. 


3) Can you run Java code without JRE?
-->No, Java bytecode cannot run without a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 

4) How is JRE different from JDK?
-->The primary difference is that the JRE is for running Java programs, while the JDK is for developing, compiling, and running Java programs.

5) What happens if your JRE version doesn’t match your JDK version?
-->A mismatch between JRE and JDK versions can lead to various runtime errors and application instability 

6) What are the components of JRE?
-->The Java Runtime Environment (JRE) is a software package that provides the necessary environment to run Java applications. 
    Its primary components include the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) (which executes bytecode), core class libraries (like java.lang,
    util, io), class loaders, and deployment tools (like Java Web Start). It acts as a layer over the operating system, facilitating software execution

7) Does JRE contain compiler tools?
-->No, the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) does not contain compiler tools. The JRE is specifically designed to provide
    the necessary environment and libraries to run compiled Java applications, not to develop or compile them. 


8) How does JRE interact with JVM?
-->The JRE (Java Runtime Environment) acts as the complete environment
    for running a Java program, within which the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) acts as the execution engine. 

9) Can you have JRE without JDK?
-->Yes, you can have the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) without the Java Development Kit (JDK)

10) Why is JRE required for end users?
-->The Java Runtime Environment (JRE) is required for end users primarily to run Java-based 
    applications on their computers without needing to develop or compile code. 




